# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-policy-k8s
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:network-policy-k8s/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] In computing, a **firewall** is a network security system that monitors and controls incoming and outgoing network traffic based on configurable security rules.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] A firewall typically establishes a barrier between a trusted network and an untrusted network, such as the Internet or between several VLANs.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Firewalls can be categorized as network-based or host-based.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] The term *firewall* originally referred to a wall to confine a fire within a line of adjacent buildings.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Later uses refer to similar structures, such as the metal sheet separating the engine compartment of a vehicle or aircraft from the passenger compartment.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] The term was applied in the 1980s to network technology that emerged when the Internet was fairly new in terms of its global use and connectivity.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] The predecessors to firewalls for network security were routers used in the 1980s.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Because they already segregated networks, routers could filter packets crossing them.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Before it was used in real-life computing, the term appeared in John Badham's 1983 computer‑hacking movie *WarGames*, spoken by the bearded and bespectacled programmer named Paul Richter, which possibly inspired its later use.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] One of the earliest commercially successful firewall and network address translation (NAT) products was the PIX (Private Internet eXchange) Firewall, invented in 1994 by Network Translation Inc., a startup founded and run by John Mayes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] The PIX Firewall technology was coded by Brantley Coile as a consultant software developer.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Recognizing the emerging IPv4 address depletion problem, they designed the PIX to enable organizations to securely connect private networks to the public internet using a limited number of registered IP addresses.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] The innovative PIX solution quickly gained industry acclaim, earning the prestigious "Hot Product of the Year" award from Data Communications Magazine in January 1995.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Cisco Systems, seeking to expand into the rapidly growing network security market, subsequently acquired Network Translation Inc. in November 1995 to obtain the rights to the PIX technology.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] The PIX became one of Cisco's flagship firewall product lines before eventually being succeeded by the Adaptive Security Appliance (ASA) platform introduced in 2005.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Firewalls are categorized as a network-based or a host-based system.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Network-based firewalls are positioned between two or more networks, typically between the local area network (LAN) and wide area network (WAN), their basic function being to control the flow of data between connected networks.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] They are either a software appliance running on general-purpose hardware, a hardware appliance running on special-purpose hardware, or a virtual appliance running on a virtual host controlled by a hypervisor.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Firewall appliances may also offer non-firewall functionality, such as DHCP or VPN services.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Host-based firewalls are deployed directly on the host itself to control network traffic or other computing resources.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] This can be a daemon or service as a part of the operating system or an agent application for protection.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] The first reported type of network firewall is called a packet filter which inspects packets transferred between computers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] The firewall maintains an access-control list which dictates what packets will be looked at and what action should be applied, if any, with the default action set to silent discard.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Three basic actions regarding the packet consist of a silent discard, discard with Internet Control Message Protocol or TCP reset response to the sender, and forward to the next hop.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Packets may be filtered by source and destination IP addresses, protocol, or source and destination ports.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] The first paper published on firewall technology was in 1987 when engineers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) developed filter systems known as packet filter firewalls.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] At AT&T Bell Labs, Bill Cheswick and Steve Bellovin continued their research in packet filtering and developed a working model for their own company based on their original first-generation architecture.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] In 1992, Steven McCanne and Van Jacobson released a paper on BSD Packet Filter (BPF) while at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] From 1989 to 1990, three colleagues from AT&T Bell Laboratories, Dave Presotto, Janardan Sharma, and Kshitij Nigam, developed the second generation of firewalls, calling them circuit-level gateways.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Marcus Ranum, Wei Xu, and Peter Churchyard released an application firewall known as Firewall Toolkit (FWTK) in October 1993.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] This became the basis for Gauntlet firewall at Trusted Information Systems.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] The key benefit of application layer filtering is that it can understand certain applications and protocols such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP), Domain Name System (DNS), or Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] This allows it to identify unwanted applications or services using a non standard port, or detect if an allowed protocol is being abused.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] It can also provide unified security management including enforced encrypted DNS and virtual private networking.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Endpoint-based application firewalls function by determining whether a process should accept any given connection.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Application firewalls filter connections by examining the process ID of data packets against a rule set for the local process involved in the data transmission.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Application firewalls accomplish their function by hooking into socket calls to filter the connections between the application layer and the lower layers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Application firewalls that hook into socket calls are also referred to as socket filters.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] At the core of a firewall's operation are the policies that govern its decision-making process.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] These policies, collectively known as firewall rules, are the specific guidelines that determine the traffic allowed or blocked across a network's boundaries.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Firewall rules are based on the evaluation of network packets against predetermined security criteria.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] A network packet, which carries data across networks, must match certain attributes defined in a rule to be allowed through the firewall.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Zones are logical segments within a network that group together devices with similar security requirements.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] By partitioning a network into zones, such as "Technical", "WAN", "LAN", "Public," "Private," "DMZ", and "Wireless," administrators can enforce policies that control the flow of traffic between them.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Each zone has its own level of trust and is governed by specific firewall rules that regulate the ingress and egress of data.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] A typical default is to allow all traffic from LAN to WAN, and to drop all traffic from WAN to LAN.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] In networking terms, services are specific functions typically identified by a network port and protocol.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Common examples include HTTP/HTTPS (web traffic) on ports 80 and 443, FTP (file transfer) on port 21, and SMTP (email) on port 25.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Services are the engines behind the applications users depend on.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] From a security aspect, controlling access to services is crucial because services are common targets for exploitation.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Firewalls employ rules that stipulate which services should be accessible, to whom, and in what context.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] For example, a firewall might be configured to block incoming FTP requests to prevent unauthorized file uploads but allow outgoing HTTPS requests for web browsing.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Applications refer to the software systems that users interact with while on the network.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] They can range from web browsers and email clients to complex database systems and cloud-based services.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] In network security, applications are important because different types of traffic can pose varying security risks.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Thus, firewall rules can be crafted to identify and control traffic based on the application generating or receiving it.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] By using application awareness, firewalls can allow, deny, or limit traffic for specific applications according to organizational policies and compliance requirements, thereby mitigating potential threats from vulnerable or undesired applications.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Application can both be a grouping of services, or a L7 inspection.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Implementing firewall rules based on IP addresses alone is often insufficient due to the dynamic nature of user location and device usage.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] User ID will be translated to an IP address.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] This is where the concept of "User ID" makes a significant impact.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] User ID allows firewall rules to be crafted based on individual user identities, rather than just fixed source or destination IP addresses.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] This enhances security by enabling more granular control over who can access certain network resources, regardless of where they are connecting from or what device they are using.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] The User ID technology is typically integrated into firewall systems through the use of directory services such as Active Directory, LDAP, RADIUS or TACACS+.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] These services link the user's login information to their network activities.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] By doing this, the firewall can apply rules and policies that correspond to user groups, roles, or individual user accounts instead of purely relying on the network topology.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Consider a school that wants to restrict access to a social media server from students.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] They can create a rule in the firewall that utilises User ID information to enforce this policy.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] User Identification — The firewall maps network traffic to specific user IDs by interpreting authentication logs.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] When a user logs on, the firewall associates that login with the user's IP address.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Define User Groups — Within the firewall's management interface, define user groups based on the directory service.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] For example, create groups such as "Students".
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] With this setup, only users who authenticate and are identified as members of "Students" are denied to access social media servers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] All other traffic, starting from LAN interfaces, will be allowed.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Setting up a firewall is a complex and error-prone task.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] A network may face security issues due to configuration errors.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Firewall policies are typically configured according to the type of network in use, such as public or private environments.
[src:network-policy-k8s/firewall-computing] Administrators define rules that permit or restrict traffic in order to reduce exposure to threats like unauthorized access, malware, or other forms of cyberattack.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:network-policy-k8s/network-segmentation] When a cyber-criminal gains unauthorized access to a network, segmentation or “zoning” can provide effective controls to limit further movement across the network.
[src:network-policy-k8s/network-segmentation] For example separating the network for Payment Card authorizations from those for Point-of-Service (till) or customer Wi-Fi traffic.
[src:network-policy-k8s/network-segmentation] A sound security policy entails segmenting the network into multiple zones, with varying security requirements, and rigorously enforcing the policy on what is allowed to move from zone to zone.
[src:network-policy-k8s/network-segmentation] Finance and Human Resources typically need access via their own VLAN to their application servers because of the confidential nature of the information they process and store.
[src:network-policy-k8s/network-segmentation] Other groups of personnel may require their own segregated networks, such as server administrators, security administration, managers and executives.
[src:network-policy-k8s/network-segmentation] Third parties are usually required to have their own segments, with different administration passwords to the main network, to avoid attacks via a compromised, less well protected, third party site.
[src:network-policy-k8s/network-segmentation] Segregation is typically achieved by a combination of firewalls and VLANs (virtual local area networks).
[src:network-policy-k8s/network-segmentation] Software-defined networking (SDN) can allow the creation and management of micro-segmented networks.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] An **overlay network** is a logical computer network that is layered on top of a physical network.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] The concept of overlay networking is distinct from the traditional model of OSI layered networks, and almost always assumes that the underlay network is an IP network of some kind.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Some examples of overlay networking technologies are, VXLAN, BGP VPNs, and IP-over-IP technologies, such as GRE, IPSEC tunnels, or SD-WAN.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Nodes in an overlay network can be thought of as being connected by logical links, each of which corresponds to a path, perhaps through many physical links, in the underlying network.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] For example, distributed systems such as peer-to-peer networks are overlay networks because their nodes form networks over existing network connections.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] The Internet was originally built as an overlay upon the telephone network, while today (through the advent of VoIP), the telephone network is increasingly turning into an overlay network built on top of the Internet.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Overlay networks have a certain set of attributes, including separation of logical addressing, security and quality of service.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Other optional attributes include resiliency, encryption and bandwidth control.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Guaranteeing bandwidth through marking traffic has multiple solutions, including IntServ and DiffServ.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] IntServ requires per-flow tracking and consequently causes scaling issues in routing platforms.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] DiffServ has been widely deployed in many operators as a method to differentiate traffic types.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] DiffServ itself provides no guarantee of throughput; it does allow the network operator to decide which traffic is higher priority, and hence will be forwarded first in congestion situations.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Overlay networks implement a much finer granularity of quality of service, allowing enterprise users to decide on an application and user or site basis which traffic should be prioritized.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Many telcos use overlay networks to provide services over their physical infrastructure.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] In the networks that connect physically diverse sites (wide area networks, WANs), one common overlay network technology is BGP VPNs.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] These VPNs are provided in the form of a service to enterprises to connect their own sites and applications.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] The advantage of these kinds of overlay networks is that the telecom operator does not need to manage addressing or other enterprise-specific network attributes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] From an enterprise point of view, while an overlay VPN service configured by the operator might fulfill their basic connectivity requirements, SD-WAN overlay networks offer additional flexibility.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] The Internet is the basis for more overlaid networks that can be constructed in order to permit routing of messages to destinations not specified by an IP address.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] For example, distributed hash tables can be used to route messages to a node having a specific logical address, whose IP address is not known in advance.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Overlay networks can be incrementally deployed at end-user sites or on hosts running the overlay protocol software, without cooperation from Internet service providers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] The overlay has no control over how packets are routed in the underlying network between two overlay nodes, but it can control, for example, the sequence of overlay nodes a message traverses before reaching its destination.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] The objective of resilience in telecommunications networks is to enable automated recovery during failure events in order to maintain a wanted service level or availability.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] As telecommunications networks are built in a layered fashion, resilience can be used in the physical, optical, IP or session to application layers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Each layer relies on the resilience features of the layer below it.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Overlay IP networks in the form of SD-WAN services therefore rely on the physical, optical and underlying IP services they are transported over.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Application-layer overlays depend on all the layers below them.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] The advantage of overlays is that they are more flexible and programmable than traditional network infrastructure, which can outweigh the disadvantages of additional latency, complexity and bandwidth overheads.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] The limited deployment of IP multicast, a best-effort network-layer multicast protocol, has led to considerable interest in alternate approaches that are implemented at the application layer in accordance with the end-to-end principle.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] In an overlay or end-system multicast approach, participating peers organize themselves into an overlay topology for data delivery.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] Each edge in this topology corresponds to a unicast path between two end-systems or peers in the underlying internet.
[src:network-policy-k8s/overlay-network] All multicast-related functionality is implemented at the peers instead of at routers, and the goal of the multicast protocol is to construct and maintain an efficient overlay for data transmission.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SDN was commonly associated with the OpenFlow protocol for remote communication with network plane elements to determine the path of network packets across network switches since OpenFlow's emergence in 2011.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] However, since 2012, proprietary systems have also used the term.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] These include Cisco Systems' Open Network Environment and Nicira's network virtualization platform.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SD-WAN applies similar technology to a wide area network (WAN).
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In addition to WAN use cases, SDN is also increasingly applied in telecom backbones, where it is paired with operational inventory and automation platforms to provide real-time visibility, service assurance, and simplified provisioning across multi-vendor networks.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The history of SDN principles can be traced back to the separation of the control and data planes first used in public switched telephone networks.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] This provided a manner of simplifying provisioning and management years before the architecture was used in data networks.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) began considering various ways to decouple the control and data forwarding functions in a proposed interface standard published in 2004 named Forwarding and Control Element Separation (ForCES).
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The ForCES Working Group also proposed a companion SoftRouter architecture.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Additional early standards from the IETF that pursued separating control from data planes include the Linux Netlink as an IP services protocol, and a path computation element (PCE)-based architecture.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] These early attempts failed to gain traction.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] One reason is that many in the Internet community viewed separating control from data to be risky, especially given the potential for failure in the control plane.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Another reason is that vendors were concerned that creating standard application programming interfaces (APIs) between the control and data planes would result in increased competition.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In 2006 a young startup was founded around SDN style network topology and submitted a collection of SDN patents in 2007.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The use of open-source software in these separated architectures traces its roots to the Ethane project at Stanford's computer science department.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Ethane's simple switch design led to the creation of OpenFlow, and an API for OpenFlow was first created in 2008.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In that same year, NOX, an operating system for networks, was created.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SDN research included emulators such as vSDNEmul, EstiNet, and Mininet.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Work on OpenFlow continued at Stanford, including with the creation of testbeds to evaluate the use of the protocol in a single campus network, as well as across the WAN as a backbone for connecting multiple campuses.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In academic settings, there were several research and production networks based on OpenFlow switches from NEC and Hewlett-Packard, as well as those based on Quanta Computer white-boxes starting in about 2009.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Beyond academia, the first deployments were by Nicira in 2010 to control OVS from Onix, codeveloped with NTT and Google.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] A notable deployment was Google's B4 in 2012.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Later, Google announced the first OpenFlow/Onix deployments in is datacenters.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Another large deployment exists at China Mobile.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The Open Networking Foundation was founded in 2011 to promote SDN and OpenFlow.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] At the 2014 Interop and Tech Field Day, software-defined networking was demonstrated by Avaya using shortest-path bridging (IEEE 802.1aq) and OpenStack as an automated campus, extending automation from the data center to the end device and removing manual provisioning from service delivery.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SDN architectures decouple network control (control plane) and forwarding (data plane) functions, enabling the network control to become directly programmable and the underlying infrastructure to be abstracted from applications and network services.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The OpenFlow protocol is one of the protocols used in SDN technologies.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The explosion of mobile devices and content, server virtualization, and the advent of cloud services are among the trends driving the networking industry to re-examine traditional network architectures.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Many conventional networks are hierarchical, built with tiers of Ethernet switches arranged in a tree structure.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] This design made sense when client-server computing was dominant, but such a static architecture may be ill-suited to the dynamic computing and storage needs of today's enterprise data centers, campuses, and carrier environments.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Within the enterprise data center, traffic patterns have changed significantly.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] At the same time, users are changing network traffic patterns as they push for access to corporate content and applications from any type of device, connecting from anywhere, at any time.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] model, which may include a private cloud, public cloud, or some mix of both, resulting in additional traffic across the wide-area network.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Users are increasingly employing mobile personal devices such as smartphones, tablets, and notebooks to access the corporate network.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] IT is under pressure to accommodate these personal devices in a fine-grained manner while protecting corporate data and intellectual property and meeting compliance mandates.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Enterprises have enthusiastically embraced both public and private cloud services, resulting in unprecedented growth of these services.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Many enterprise businesses want the agility to access applications, infrastructure and other IT resources on demand and discretely.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] IT planning for cloud services must be performed in an environment of increased security, compliance and auditing requirements, along with business reorganizations, consolidations and mergers that can rapidly change assumptions.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Providing self-service provisioning, whether in a private or public cloud, requires elastic scaling of computing, storage and network resources, ideally from a common viewpoint and with a common suite of tools.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] requires massive parallel processing on thousands of servers, all of which need direct connections to each other.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] is fueling a constant demand for additional network capacity in the data center.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Operators of hyperscale data center networks face the daunting task of scaling the network to previously unimaginable size, maintaining any-to-any connectivity within a limited budget.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] emerged, the need for larger data centers has increased the energy consumption of those facilities.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] applying existing routing techniques to dynamically adjust the network data plane to save energy.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Also techniques to improve control plane energy efficiency are being researched.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In addition, they may consume an abstracted view of the network for their internal decision-making purposes.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] An SDN Application consists of SDN application logic and one or more NBI drivers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SDN applications may themselves expose another layer of abstracted network control, thus offering one or more higher-level NBIs through respective NBI agents.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The SDN controller is a logically centralized entity in charge of (i) translating the requirements from the SDN application layer down to the SDN datapaths and (ii) providing the SDN applications with an abstract view of the network (which may include statistics and events).
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] An SDN controller consists of one or more NBI agents, the SDN control logic, and the control to data-plane interface (CDPI) driver.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The SDN datapath is a logical network device that exposes visibility and uncontested control over its advertised forwarding and data processing capabilities.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The logical representation may encompass all or a subset of the capabilities.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath consists of a CDPI agent and a set of one or more traffic forwarding engines and zero or more traffic processing functions.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] These engines and functions may include simple forwarding between the datapath's external interfaces or internal traffic processing or termination functions.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] One or more SDN datapaths may be contained in a single (physical) network element—an integrated physical combination of communications resources, managed as a unit.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] An SDN datapath may also be defined across multiple physical network elements.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The SDN CDPI is the interface defined between an SDN controller and an SDN datapath, which provides at least programmatic control of all forwarding operations, capabilities advertisement, statistics reporting, and event notification.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] One value of SDN lies in the expectation that the CDPI is implemented in an open, vendor-neutral and interoperable way.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SDN NBIs are interfaces between SDN applications and SDN controllers and typically provide abstract network views and enable direct expression of network behavior and requirements.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] This may occur at any level of abstraction and across different sets of functionality.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The implementation of the SDN control plane can follow a centralized, hierarchical, or decentralized design.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Initial SDN control plane proposals focused on a centralized solution, where a single control entity had a global view of the network.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] While this simplifies the implementation of the control logic, it has scalability limitations as the size and dynamics of the network increase.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] To overcome these limitations, hierarchical and distributed approaches have been proposed.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In hierarchical solutions, controllers operate on a partitioned network view, while decisions that require network-wide knowledge are taken by a logically centralized root controller.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In distributed approaches, controllers operate on their local view or they may exchange synchronization messages to enhance their knowledge.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Distributed solutions are more suitable for supporting adaptive SDN applications.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] A key issue when designing a distributed SDN control plane is to decide on the number and placement of control entities.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] An important parameter to consider while doing so is the propagation delay between the controllers and the network devices, especially in the context of large networks.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Other objectives that have been considered involve control path reliability, fault tolerance, and application requirements.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In SDN, the data plane is responsible for processing data-carrying packets using a set of rules specified by the control plane.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The data plane may be implemented in physical hardware switches or in software, such as Open vSwitch.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The memory capacity of hardware switches may limit the number of rules that can be stored whereas software implementations may have higher capacity.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Flow table entries may be populated in a proactive, reactive, or hybrid fashion.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In the proactive mode, the controller populates flow table entries for all possible traffic matches for this switch in advance.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] This mode can be compared with typical routing table entries today, where all static entries are installed ahead of time.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Following this, no request is sent to the controller since all incoming flows will find a matching entry.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] A major advantage in proactive mode is that all packets are forwarded at line rate (considering all flow table entries in TCAM) and no delay is added.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In the reactive mode, entries are populated on demand.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] If a packet arrives without a corresponding match rule in the flow table, the SDN agent sends a request to the controller for further instruction.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The controller examines the SDN agent requests and provides instructions, installing a rule in the flow table for the corresponding packet if necessary.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The hybrid mode uses the low-latency proactive forwarding mode for a portion of traffic while relying on the flexibility of reactive mode processing for the remaining traffic.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Software-defined mobile networking (SDMN) is an approach to the design of mobile networks where all protocol-specific features are implemented in software, maximizing the use of generic and commodity hardware and software in both the core network and radio access network.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] It is proposed as an extension of SDN paradigm to incorporate mobile network specific functionalities.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Since 3GPP Rel.14, a Control User Plane Separation was introduced in the Mobile Core Network architectures with the PFCP protocol.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] An SD-WAN is a WAN managed using the principles of software-defined networking.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The main driver of SD-WAN is to lower WAN costs using more affordable and commercially available leased lines, as an alternative or partial replacement of more expensive MPLS lines.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Control and management are administered separately from the hardware, with central controllers allowing for easier configuration and administration.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] An SD-LAN is a Local area network (LAN) built around the principles of software-defined networking, though there are key differences in topology, network security, application visibility and control, management and quality of service.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SD-LAN decouples control, management and data planes to enable a policy-driven architecture for wired and wireless LANs.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SD-LANs are characterized by their use of a cloud management system and wireless connectivity without the presence of a physical controller.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SDN architecture may enable, facilitate or enhance network-related security applications due to the controller's central view of the network, and its capacity to modify behavior or the data plane at any time.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The security implications of SDN architecture remain under study.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Several research works on SDN have already investigated security applications built upon the SDN controller, with different aims in mind.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Distributed denial of service (DDoS) detection and mitigation, as well as botnet and worm propagation, are some concrete use cases of such applications.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Proposed applications periodically collect network statistics from the forwarding plane of the network in a standardized manner (e.g., using OpenFlow), and then apply classification algorithms on those statistics in order to detect any network anomalies.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] If an anomaly is detected, the application instructs the controller how to reprogram the data plane in order to mitigate it.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Another kind of security application leverages the SDN controller by implementing some moving target defense (MTD) algorithms.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] MTD algorithms are typically used to make any attack on a given system or network more difficult than usual by periodically hiding or changing key properties of that system or network.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In traditional networks, implementing MTD algorithms is not a trivial task since it is difficult to build a central authority able to determine, for each part of the system to be protected, which key properties are hidden or changed.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In an SDN network, such tasks become more straightforward thanks to the centrality of the controller.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] One application can, for example, periodically assign virtual IPs to hosts within the network, and the mapping of virtual IP to real IP is then performed by the controller.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Another application can simulate some fake opened/closed/filtered ports on random hosts in the network in order to add significant noise during scanning performed by an attacker.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Additional value regarding security in SDN-enabled networks can also be gained using FlowVisor and FlowChecker.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The former tries to use a single hardware forwarding plane sharing multiple separated logical networks.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Following this approach, the same hardware resources can be used for production and development purposes as well as separating monitoring, configuration and Internet traffic, where each scenario can have its own logical topology, which is called a slice.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] In conjunction with this approach, FlowChecker realizes the validation of new OpenFlow rules that are deployed by users using their own slice.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SDN controller applications are mostly deployed in large-scale scenarios, which requires comprehensive checks of possible programming errors.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] A system to do this called NICE was described in 2012.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Introducing an overarching security architecture requires a comprehensive and protracted approach to SDN.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Since it was introduced, designers are looking at possible ways to secure SDN that do not compromise scalability.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] One architecture called SN-SECA (SDN+NFV) Security Architecture.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Distributed applications that run across datacenters usually replicate data for the purpose of synchronization, fault resiliency, load balancing and getting data closer to users (which reduces latency to users and increases their perceived throughput).
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Also, many applications, such as Hadoop, replicate data within a datacenter across multiple racks to increase fault tolerance and make data recovery easier.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] All of these operations require data delivery from one machine or datacenter to multiple machines or datacenters.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] The process of reliably delivering data from one machine to multiple machines is referred to as Reliable Group Data Delivery (RGDD).
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SDN switches can be used for RGDD via installation of rules that allow forwarding to multiple outgoing ports.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] For example, OpenFlow provides support for Group Tables since version 1.1 which makes this possible.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Using SDN, a central controller can carefully and intelligently setup forwarding trees for RGDD.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Such trees can be built while paying attention to network congestion/load status to improve performance.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] For example, MCTCP is a scheme for delivery to many nodes inside datacenters that relies on regular and structured topologies of datacenter networks while DCCast and QuickCast are approaches for fast and efficient data and content replication across datacenters over private WANs.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Network Function Virtualization, or NFV for short, is a concept that complements SDN.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Thus, NFV is not dependent on SDN or SDN concepts.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] NFV separates software from hardware to enable flexible network deployment and dynamic operation.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] NFV deployments typically use commodity servers to run network services software versions that previously were hardware-based.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] These software-based services that run in an NFV environment are called Virtual Network Functions (VNF).
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SDN-NFV hybrid program was provided for high efficiency, elastic and scalable capabilities NFV aimed at accelerating service innovation and provisioning using standard IT virtualization technologies.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] SDN provides the agility of controlling the generic forwarding devices such as the routers and switches by using SDN controllers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] On the other hand, NFV agility is provided for the network applications by using virtualized servers.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] It is entirely possible to implement a virtualized network function (VNF) as a standalone entity using existing networking and orchestration paradigms.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] However, there are inherent benefits in leveraging SDN concepts to implement and manage an NFV infrastructure, particularly when looking at the management and orchestration of VNFs, and that's why multivendor platforms are being defined that incorporate SDN and NFV in concerted ecosystems.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Deep packet inspection (DPI) provides network with application-awareness, while SDN provides applications with network-awareness.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] Although SDN will radically change the generic network architectures, it should cope with working with traditional network architectures to offer high interoperability.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] When using an SDN based model for transmitting multimedia traffic, an important aspect to take account is the QoE estimation.
[src:network-policy-k8s/software-defined-networking] To estimate the QoE, first we have to be able to classify the traffic and then, it's recommended that the system can solve critical problems on its own by analyzing the traffic.
